<p style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.85em;color:#888">Updated July 2026 &middot; 8 min read</p>
<h1>Nitroglycerin vs Nitroprusside — Two Vasodilator Drips, Two Jobs</h1>
<p class="hub-crumb" style="font-family:sans-serif;font-size:0.9em;background:#f0f4ff;border-left:4px solid #3b6cf8;padding:8px 14px;border-radius:0 6px 6px 0;margin:14px 0;">Part of the <a href="icu-pharmacology-hub-2026.html"><strong>ICU Pharmacology Hub</strong></a> &mdash; browse every related guide in one place.</p>
<p style="font-size:1.15em;color:#444">Nitroglycerin and nitroprusside (Nipride) are the two titratable vasodilator infusions you'll run for hypertensive emergencies and acute heart failure. They sound interchangeable &mdash; both are nitric-oxide donors, both drop blood pressure minute-to-minute &mdash; but they dilate different parts of the circulation and carry very different toxicities. Nitroglycerin mostly unloads the veins; nitroprusside opens veins <em>and</em> arteries and hides a cyanide problem. Getting the distinction clear keeps your titration safe.</p>
<div class="hero-note">
<strong>The short version:</strong> <strong>Nitroglycerin</strong> is primarily a <em>venodilator</em> at usual doses (reduces preload, relieves cardiac ischemia and pulmonary congestion), arterial only at high doses, and it develops <strong>tolerance</strong> over 24&ndash;48 hours. <strong>Nitroprusside</strong> is a balanced arterial-and-venous dilator with near-instant, precise control of blood pressure &mdash; but it can cause <strong>cyanide/thiocyanate toxicity</strong>, especially at high doses, prolonged use, or in renal/hepatic impairment, and it must be protected from light. Both demand an arterial line and continuous titration.</p>
</div>

<h2>Different vessels, different jobs</h2>
<p><strong>Nitroglycerin</strong> at typical infusion rates works mainly on the <strong>venous</strong> side. By dilating veins it reduces <em>preload</em> &mdash; the volume returning to the heart &mdash; which lowers wall stress, relieves pulmonary congestion in acute heart failure/flash pulmonary edema, and dilates coronary arteries to relieve <strong>myocardial ischemia</strong>. That's why nitroglycerin is the vasodilator of choice when the problem is <em>cardiac</em>: ACS with hypertension, heart failure, or ischemic chest pain. Only at higher doses does it add meaningful arterial dilation.</p>
<p><strong>Nitroprusside</strong> is a <strong>balanced</strong> dilator: it opens arteries and veins at once, cutting both afterload and preload. That gives it fast, powerful, finely titratable control of blood pressure, which is why it shines in true <strong>hypertensive emergencies</strong> and settings like aortic dissection (paired with a beta-blocker for rate control) where you need to bring pressure down smoothly and predictably. Its onset and offset are almost immediate &mdash; turn the drip and the pressure follows within a minute or two.</p>

<h2>The tolerance problem with nitroglycerin</h2>
<div class="warning">
<strong>Nitroglycerin tolerance is real and fast.</strong> Within 24&ndash;48 hours of a continuous infusion, effectiveness fades and you find yourself titrating higher for the same result. This isn't the patient "getting worse" &mdash; it's pharmacologic tolerance. The team may plan nitrate-free intervals or transition to another agent. Also expect <strong>headache</strong> (very common), reflex tachycardia, and hypotension, and know that nitroglycerin is <strong>absolutely contraindicated</strong> with recent PDE-5 inhibitors (sildenafil/tadalafil) &mdash; the combination causes catastrophic hypotension.</div>

<h2>The cyanide problem with nitroprusside</h2>
<div class="warning">
<strong>Nitroprusside metabolizes into cyanide, then thiocyanate.</strong> Its power comes with a toxic tail: each molecule releases cyanide, which is normally detoxified to thiocyanate and cleared renally. At <strong>high doses, prolonged infusions, or in renal/hepatic impairment</strong>, cyanide or thiocyanate accumulates. Watch for <strong>unexplained metabolic (lactic) acidosis, altered mental status, worsening venous oxygen saturation, and tachyphylaxis</strong> (needing ever-higher doses for the same effect) &mdash; those can signal cyanide toxicity. Thiocyanate toxicity shows as confusion, tinnitus, and seizures, especially in kidney disease. Use the lowest effective dose for the shortest time, and escalate concerns early.</div>
<p>Nitroprusside is also <strong>light-sensitive</strong> &mdash; the bag and often the tubing are protected from light per pharmacy protocol &mdash; and a change in the solution's color can indicate degradation. These aren't optional niceties; they're part of safe administration.</p>

<table>
<tr><th> </th><th>Nitroglycerin</th><th>Nitroprusside (Nipride)</th></tr>
<tr><td>Main effect</td><td>Venodilation (preload &darr;)</td><td>Balanced arterial + venous</td></tr>
<tr><td>Best for</td><td>Cardiac ischemia, HF/pulmonary edema</td><td>Hypertensive emergency, dissection*</td></tr>
<tr><td>Onset/offset</td><td>Fast</td><td>Near-instant, very titratable</td></tr>
<tr><td>Signature problem</td><td>Tolerance in 24&ndash;48 h; headache</td><td>Cyanide/thiocyanate toxicity</td></tr>
<tr><td>Special handling</td><td>Avoid with PDE-5 inhibitors</td><td>Light-protected; caution in renal/hepatic dz</td></tr>
<tr><td>Monitoring</td><td>BP, HR, headache, tolerance</td><td>BP, acid-base, lactate, mental status</td></tr>
</table>
<p style="font-size:0.85em;color:#777">*In aortic dissection, a beta-blocker is given first/with it to control heart rate and shear stress.</p>

<h2>How the team chooses</h2>
<p>If the driving problem is the <strong>heart</strong> &mdash; ischemia, chest pain, heart failure with congestion &mdash; nitroglycerin's preload reduction and coronary dilation make it the natural pick. If the driving problem is <strong>severe, refractory hypertension</strong> needing precise second-to-second control &mdash; a hypertensive emergency, controlled reduction in dissection &mdash; nitroprusside's balanced, instantly titratable effect is hard to beat, with the cyanide caveat keeping infusions short and doses conservative. Many units now favor nicardipine or clevidipine over nitroprusside for routine hypertensive emergencies precisely to avoid the cyanide risk, reserving nitroprusside for when its rapid titratability is truly needed.</p>
<div class="callout">
<strong>Bedside monitoring, in short:</strong> Both need an <strong>arterial line</strong> and a controlled, controlled-descent approach (drop the pressure smoothly, roughly 10&ndash;20% in the first hour, not off a cliff). On nitroglycerin, expect headache and watch for creeping tolerance; screen for recent PDE-5 inhibitors. On nitroprusside, keep it light-protected, use the lowest effective dose, and treat unexplained acidosis, rising lactate, or new confusion as possible cyanide toxicity &mdash; especially in kidney disease or after prolonged infusion.</p>
</div>

